{"parse":{"title":"Society for the Arts, Religion and Contemporary Culture","pageid":6746841,"revid":794685351,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>The Society for the Arts, Religion, and Contemporary Culture</b>, or <b>ARC</b>, was founded in October 1961 by three people, Alfred Barr, the art critic and founder of the <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Modern_Art\" title=\"Museum of Modern Art\">Museum of Modern Art</a>, the theologian <a href=\"/wiki/Paul_Tillich\" title=\"Paul Tillich\">Paul Tillich</a>, and Marvin Halverson an American Protestant theologian sometime of the <a href=\"/wiki/Chicago_Theological_Seminary\" title=\"Chicago Theological Seminary\">Chicago Theological Seminary</a> and the author of a 1951 booklet, <i>Great Religious Paintings</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Its aims and program are based on the deep and complex relationship between religion and the arts.  Its first board of directors included these three as well as <a href=\"/wiki/Unitarian_Universalist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Unitarian Universalist\">Unitarian Universalist</a> theologian and parish minister, <a href=\"/wiki/James_Luther_Adams\" title=\"James Luther Adams\">James Luther Adams</a>; mythologist <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Campbell\" title=\"Joseph Campbell\">Joseph Campbell</a>, principal developer of the merger forming the <a href=\"/wiki/United_Church_of_Christ\" title=\"United Church of Christ\">United Church of Christ</a>, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Truman_B._Douglass&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Truman B. Douglass (page does not exist)\">Truman B. Douglass</a>; Congregationalist parish minister and theologian <a href=\"/wiki/Amos_Wilder\" title=\"Amos Wilder\">Amos Wilder</a>, and <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Stanley_Romaine_Hopper&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Stanley Romaine Hopper (page does not exist)\">Stanley Romaine Hopper</a>, theologian and co-founder of the first Theology and Literature program in the United States.\n</p><p>Among the more than 300 Fellows of the Society have been <a href=\"/wiki/Mircea_Eliade\" title=\"Mircea Eliade\">Mircea Eliade</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Denise_Levertov\" title=\"Denise Levertov\">Denise Levertov</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sallie_McFague\" title=\"Sallie McFague\">Sallie McFague</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Cleanth_Brooks\" title=\"Cleanth Brooks\">Cleanth Brooks</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Marianne_Moore\" title=\"Marianne Moore\">Marianne Moore</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/W._H._Auden\" title=\"W. H. Auden\">W. H. Auden</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/John_Updike\" title=\"John Updike\">John Updike</a>.\n</p><p>During the late 1960s most of the individuals involved in the published discourse pertaining to the field of <a href=\"/wiki/Theopoetics\" title=\"Theopoetics\">theopoetics</a> were either fellows or members of SARCC.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  Another major focus of the Society has been the role of myth in culture resulting in two publications.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Presently SARCC sponsors public lectures and currently publishes a newsletter, Seedbed. Previously it has published a periodical entitled \"ARC Directions.\"\n</p><p>The archives of SARCC are maintained at the <a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Divinity_School#Andover-Harvard_Theological_Library\" title=\"Harvard Divinity School\">Andover-Harvard Theological Library</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Library_Holdings_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Library_Holdings-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Society_for_the_Arts,_Religion_and_Contemporary_Culture&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Halverson M., <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://lccn.loc.gov/54004313\"><i>Great Religious Paintings</i></a>, New York, H. N. Abrams, 1951.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Keefe-Perry, L. B. C. (2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://theopoetics.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/Theopoetics-Process-and-Perspective1.pdf\">\"Christianity and Literature\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>Christianity and Literature</i>. <b>58</b> (4)<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved 11/10/2012</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Christianity+and+Literature&amp;rft.atitle=Christianity+and+Literature&amp;rft.volume=58&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.aulast=Keefe-Perry&amp;rft.aufirst=L.+B.+C.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Ftheopoetics.net%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2010%2F11%2FTheopoetics-Process-and-Perspective1.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASociety+for+the+Arts%2C+Religion+and+Contemporary+Culture\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Check date values in: <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;accessdate=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#bad_date\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Campbe